==English==
===Etymology===
[[Middle French]] ''interposer,'' modification (influenced by ''poser'' to put, place) of Latin ''interponere'' ([[perfect]] stem ''interpos-''), from ''inter-'' + ''ponere'' to put, place
===Verb===
#'''a.''' ''transitive'' to place between (in space or time); to put or set between or in an intermediate position; to cause to intervene. Often with implication of obstruction or delay '''b.''' ''obsolete'' to place (things) with intervals, or in alternation, to cause to alternate. '''c.''' ''chess.'' to move (a man) so as to obstruct the line of action of an opposing piece, ''especially'' when the latter is giving check. ''also,'' or with the interposed man as subject. 
#to place or station oneself between; to come between in position, to stand in the way. 
#''transitive'' to put forth or introduce (action, authority, etc.) in the way of interference or intervention
#To put oneself forward or interfere in a matter; to step in between persons at variance or in a person's behalf; to intervene
#'''a.''' ''transitive.'' to introduce between other matters, or between the parts of a narrative, as an interruption or digression; to say or pronounce as an interruption. '''b.''' ''intransitive.'' to interrupt, make a digression
#'''a.''' ''obsolete; transitive.'' to come or be in the way of (a person or thing); to intercept; to obstruct. '''b.''' to lie between (places); to part, separate

===Noun===
''obsolete.'' interposition, interposal